2. Core DBMS Concepts Used

Primary Key
“Primary key uniquely identifies every record in a table.”
Example: user_id, complaint_id, department_id.

Foreign Key
“Foreign key connects two tables and maintains referential integrity.”

Example: complaint table may contain user_id and department_id to link complaint with user and department.

Constraints
“Constraints prevent invalid data from entering the database.”

Examples:

NOT NULL: required fields
CHECK: priority only low/medium/high
UNIQUE: email unique
FOREIGN KEY: valid references only

README mentions 20+ integrity constraints.

3. Why PostgreSQL is Important Here

“PostgreSQL is not just storing data; it is enforcing rules, maintaining audit accountability, calculating resolution time, and supporting analytics.”

This makes project DBMS-heavy, not just frontend-backend.

4. Priority Tradeoff — Most Important Concept

This is a very good viva point.

Problem:

Fully automated priority can misclassify.
Fully manual priority can be misused.

Your solution:

“I chose user-declared priority with SLA differentiation and analytical monitoring. This gives users contextual fairness while still allowing the admin to monitor priority misuse.”

Simple example:

“A hostel water issue may feel high priority to a student, so the user declares priority. But if too many high-priority complaints come from one category/user, analytics can detect inflation.”

5. SLA Explanation

SLA = Service Level Agreement
“SLA means expected resolution time for a complaint.”

Example:

High priority → resolve faster
Medium priority → normal timeline
Low priority → longer timeline

Viva line:

“Priority is not just a label; it is mapped to SLA-tiered resolution timelines.”

6. Audit Logging

Audit logging means:

“Every important complaint transition is recorded — who changed it, when changed it, and what changed.”

Example:

Complaint status:
open → assigned → in_progress → resolved → closed
Whenever status changes, trigger inserts record into audit table.

Viva line:

“Audit logs provide accountability and make the system transparent.”
README mentions automated audit logging using database triggers and lifecycle transitions.

7. Triggers

Trigger ka answer:

“A trigger is a database object that automatically executes when an event like INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE happens.”

In your project:

“I used PL/pgSQL triggers to automate audit logging and resolution-time calculation.”

Example:

When complaint status becomes resolved,
database automatically calculates resolution time.

8.Normalization / 3NF

README says schema is normalized to 3NF.

Viva answer:

“The database is normalized to 3NF to reduce redundancy, avoid update anomalies, and keep data consistent.”

Example:

Instead of storing department name repeatedly in every complaint:

Department table:
department_id, department_name
Complaint table:
complaint_id, department_id

This avoids repeated data.

9.Roles

There are 3 roles:

Student
Can raise complaints, select category and priority, track status.

Staff
Can view assigned complaints, update progress, resolve complaints.

Admin
Can monitor workload, SLA compliance, priority distribution, analytics.

Viva line:
“Role-based governance ensures every user has controlled access according to responsibility.”

